ally different from what occurred in Europe. In States and Power in Africa, Jeffrey Herbst places the African state-building process in a truly comparative perspective. Herbst's bold contention—that the conditions now facing African state-builders existed long before European penetration of the continent—is sure to provoke controversy, for it runs counter to the prevailing assumption that colonialism changed everything.This revised edition includes a new preface in which the author links the enormous changes that have taken place in Africa over the past fifteen years to long-term state consolidation. The final chapter on policy prescriptions has also been revised to reflect the evolution of African and international responses to state failure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPower (Social sciences)zAfrica. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAfrican Problem.  aAfrican politics.  aEurope.  aEuropean colonialism.  aWest Africa.  aagriculture.  aauthority.  aautonomy.  aboundaries.  achiefs.  acitizenship.  acolonial Africa.  acolonialism.  acurrency.  aelites.  aethnic groups.  ahegemony.  aindependent Africa.  ainternational relations.  aland allocation.  aland tenure.  aland.  amigration.  anation-states.  anational design.  apeace.  apolicy.  apolitical geography.  apolitics.  apopulation movements.  apower.  aprecolonial Africa.  aproperty rights.  arefugees.  arural areas.  asovereignty.  aspace.  astate consolidation.  astate failure.  astate-building.  astates.  aterritory.1 aHerbst, Jeffrey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140085232140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/is